dspace-development.title: Provide the file system export for Symplectic Elements server environments

comments.body: FileZilla could not be installed on the Windows Server `production` and `development` environments for Elements. I am going to proceed and see about advancing this myself.

It seems to be the case that outbound traffic for the hosts may be blocked when attempting to use a FTP client:

![image.png](https://images.zenhubusercontent.com/5b5b6aed981c3204c9ed06c8/1f674fa1-0628-4a32-b610-8c2b58951976)

OIT has been made aware of this by e-mail, and they are currently investigating the restrictions set by the firewall.

Please note that attempting to transmit `ping` requests to servers accessible to the University network seems to raise some DNS errors:

![image.png](https://images.zenhubusercontent.com/5b5b6aed981c3204c9ed06c8/1f540a56-72cb-4bd2-a651-30f3c7212644)

While the requested port for the SFTP was opened, now the following error message is being logged:

```powsh
 No supported authentication methods available (server sent: publickey)

PS C:\windows\system32> & 'C:\Program Files\PuTTY\pscp.exe' -v -sftp -batch -pw $Secret -hostkey 'SHA256:IpnamxYhbsSWW4Fqe3WB/f53ANd6kq+BNN3A+FtvPmg' 'C:\temp\test.txt' 'princeton@ftp.use.symplectic.org:/' 
```

Perhaps the problem is due to only FTP (not over SSH) being supported?
The `WinSCP` client for Windows environments does support FTPS (FTP over TLS), but this may require another firewall request.

comments.body:
The following errors were logged while trying to install the DataDog client on the server:

```bash
TASK [roles/datadog : Ensure Datadog repository is up-to-date] ***********************************************************************
fatal: [oawaiver-staging1.princeton.edu]: FAILED! => {"changed": false, "msg": "Failed to update apt cache: W:GPG error: https://apt.datadoghq.com stable Release: The following signatures couldn't be verified because the public key is not available: NO_PUBKEY 33EE313BAD9589B7, E:The repository 'https://apt.datadoghq.com stable Release' is not signed., W:Updating from such a repository can't be done securely, and is therefore disabled by default., W:See apt-secure(8) manpage for repository creation and user configuration details., W:Skipping acquire of configured file 'Release/binary-amd64/Packages' as repository 'https://oss-binaries.phusionpassenger.com/apt/passenger bionic InRelease' doesn't have the component 'Release' (component misspelt in sources.list?), W:Skipping acquire of configured file 'Release/binary-i386/Packages' as repository 'https://oss-binaries.phusionpassenger.com/apt/passenger bionic InRelease' doesn't have the component 'Release' (component misspelt in sources.list?), W:Skipping acquire of configured file 'Release/i18n/Translation-en_US' as repository 'https://oss-binaries.phusionpassenger.com/apt/passenger bionic InRelease' doesn't have the component 'Release' (component misspelt in sources.list?), W:Skipping acquire of configured file 'Release/i18n/Translation-en' as repository 'https://oss-binaries.phusionpassenger.com/apt/passenger bionic InRelease' doesn't have the component 'Release' (component misspelt in sources.list?)"}
```

This seems to be the root cause of the problem:

```bash
W: GPG error: https://apt.datadoghq.com stable Release: The following signatures couldn't be verified because the public key is not available: NO_PUBKEY 33EE313BAD9589B7
```
An invalid API key seems to be missing from the server configurations for the DataDog agent installations.

comments.body: The display looks good now with ASpace exports when testing locally, except the PDFs since I don't have them on my machine. I left a note in the README on how to test.
One of the Figgy parts of this process has been removed (the part that updated the DAOs to point to local PDFs instead of at Figgy). But I think we should merge this and fix that separately.
One of the Figgy parts of this process has been removed (the part that updated the DAOs to point to local PDFs instead of at Figgy). But I think we should merge this and fix that separately.
In which file would that have happened? (I'm pretty sure I didn't touch dao...)

@regineheberlein Sorry, I mean removed from Figgy — there was one Rake task to export PDFs and a second one to update the EAD XML to point to the PDFs instead of to HTTP URLs (this second task was removed). I think we can probably just update `spv.xsl` to do this part instead of restoring the Figgy code which is pretty complex because it's related to the old code to add the DAOs pointing to Figgy in the first place).
Ah, removed from Figgy! Ok. You had me worried there for a sec!
Looks like it would be this template--what does it need to do differently? ``` btn small _blank View PDF ```
Instead of the Figgy URL from `@xlink:href`, it should link to the PDF files on disk, which are named after the component IDs (e.g., `pdf/c3.pdf`)

Ok, I'll add that. Interestingly, it looks like C1491 already has dao's that do that, but they're in addition to figgy-style ones. Whereas C0686 only has the figgy-style ones. ```

View digital content

View digital content

 ```

Oh, I bet those DAOs linking to `pdf/c105.pdf` were accidentally added and should probably be removed. The old process updated the files on disk and then reverted the changes after the export — if that went wrong, I can imagine the separate process that added the DAO links to Figgy committing those by mistake.
I'll give Will Clements a heads-up about removing those dao's before I actually do it.
